1. What are CSS Custom Variables?
Custom Variables (commonly called CSS Variables) allow you to store specific values—like colors, fonts, or padding spacing—in one central location and reuse them throughout your entire stylesheet. This makes changing a website's theme or color palette later incredibly simple.

Syntax & Scope
Declaring Variables: To create a variable, you choose a name and prefix it with two dashes (--).

Global Scope (:root): Placing your variables inside the :root selector makes them accessible to every single element across your whole webpage.

Using Variables (var()): To apply a variable, wrap its custom name inside the var() function.

CSS
/* 1. Declare global theme variables */
:root {
  --primary-color: #007bff;
  --secondary-color: #6c757d;
  --main-padding: 1.5rem;
  --heading-font: 'Poppins', sans-serif;
}

/* 2. Reuse them anywhere in your stylesheet */
.card {
  background-color: var(--primary-color);
  padding: var(--main-padding);
}

h1 {
  font-family: var(--heading-font);
  color: var(--secondary-color);
}
2. Understanding Responsive Web Design & Media Queries
A Media Query is a CSS block directive that tells the browser: "Only execute this specific styling layout IF the user's hardware matches these conditions (like screen width, height, or orientation)." This is the core engine behind mobile-friendly development.

Core Structure of a Media Query
CSS
@media media-type and (media-feature) {
  /* This custom CSS compiles ONLY when the rule above is TRUE */
}
Media Types: screen (desktop monitors, phones, tablets), print (printers), or all.

Media Features: Conditional constraints like max-width, min-width, or orientation.

3. Practical Positioning: Screen Breakpoints
Breakpoints are the specific screen width thresholds where your layout alters configuration to accommodate smaller viewports.

A. Mobile-First vs. Desktop-First Approaches
Desktop-First (max-width): You style the massive desktop monitor layout first, then use max-width to strip away or modify items as the screen shrinks down to mobile size.

Mobile-First (min-width): You style the compact mobile layout first, then scale up as screen dimensions expand.

B. Example Real-World Implementation (Desktop-First)
In this example, the grid container automatically downscales from 3 columns on a desktop to 1 single column on a small smartphone screen:

CSS
/* Baseline Desktop Layout */
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row; /* Side-by-side elements */
  background-color: lightgray;
}

/* --- MEDIA QUERY BREAKPOINTS --- */

/* 1. Tablets (Screens 768px wide or smaller) */
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  :root {
    --main-padding: 1rem; /* Dynamically decrease global variable padding spacing */
  }
  .container {
    background-color: lightblue; /* Visual change for tablet tracking testing */
  }
}

/* 2. Mobile Phones (Screens 480px wide or smaller) */
@media screen and (max-width: 480px) {
  .container {
    flex-direction: column; /* Stacks column boxes vertically on small devices */
    background-color: lightcoral;
  }
}
4. Key Takeaways for Students
Dynamic Pairing: You can nest variable overrides inside your media queries. When the screen drops past a mobile threshold, updating --primary-color inside @media immediately shifts colors across your entire architecture cleanly.

Never duplicate layout frameworks: Media queries should only contain the tiny, distinct property changes needed to alter alignments at that breakpoint. Do not copy paste your entire baseline element rules into them.